title: I could have easily just served him a Costco corndog instead.

images.description:
My Dad is rapidly declining from dementia and couldn't really appreciate this but I wanted to do it for him anyway.

Grilled butterflied chicken stuffed with spinach, parmesan, and garlic on top of pasta with shredded mozzarella, asiago, and provolone with a white wine reduction marinara alfredo sauce with a small side of broccoli.

Even 10 years ago and his reaction to this meal would have been hugely different. This was the kind of food he used to order and rave about. I could have given him a standard TV dinner now and he wouldn't have batted an eye. 

Still, I put time and love into this. It was just for the two of us for dinner and it was worth it.

Most viral edit: Holy cow guys. Y'all are the best! Thanks for all the love and support.  Don't send anything. Maybe just call or text a loved one today. Life is short and precious.

title: Climate activist Greta Thunberg detained by police in Germany at coal mine protest

images.description:
Sorry, was in usersub and saw some pictures of her being detained and had no idea what was up.

That made me look it up, so I thought I'd share!

Climate activist Greta Thunberg has been detained by German police at a protest over the expansion of a coal mine in the west German village of Lützerath.

This is the second time Thunberg has been detained at the site, police spokesperson Christof Hüls told CNN Tuesday. She was part of a large group of protesters that broke through a police barrier and encroached on a coal pit, which authorities have not been able to secure entirely, Hüls said.

After the group advanced on the coal pit, police were concerned that the “masses of protesters” could set the ground in motion after it had been softened by rainfall during the last few days. Officers intervened, removing people from the “danger area” and detaining them, one of whom was Thunberg, according to police.

“We knew who she was, but she did not get VIP treatment,” Hüls said. “She did not resist,” he added.

Thunberg had been the main speaker at the rally on Saturday and had “surprisingly” returned to protest on Sunday when she was detained the first time and then again on Tuesday, he said.

More here:

title: Unusual facts about Sweden, 17: Falu rödfärg

images.description: New unusual facts about Sweden every day 2023, day 17: Falu rödfärg (Falu red paint color). People visiting the swedish country side have noticed how common this red color is on houses made from wood. The red little cabin by the lake or forrest is a symbol of Sweden.
As far as summer projects go painting with Falu rödfärg is nice. Just brush all the debris from the wall and start painting.

This is the Falu copper mine giving the color/paint it's name. People have been mining here from the 8th century up to 1992. Mostly for copper but also gold, silver, other metals and minerals. Actually it was the biggest copper mine in the world in the 18th century.

title: Mexican attempts to make honey cake

images.description:
12 layers of honey crackers, 13 layers of cream, a sprinkle of salt between some layers, and some raw honey between others.

It tastes like toasted honey and melts in your mouth, super soft and light.

Honey crackers:
Cream 3 eggs with 180g of sugar until fluffy, beat in 300g of honey until homogenized, then fold in 375 ap flour, a good pinch or two of salt, and 8g of baking soda

Spread very thinly 1mm or so into silicone or parchment and cook at 320F for 9 min.

Cream filling:
250g heavy whipping cream whipped with 60g powdered sugar until a tiny bit more than medium peaks, fold in 500g of full fat sour cream.

Refrigerate overnight. https://youtube.com/shorts/VYmhCYV5AHg

title: Russian Sergeant Blows Up Own Troops in Bid to 'Establish Authority'

images.description:
An explosion in Russia's Belgorod region that killed three soldiers and injured 16 others was caused by a sergeant who set off a grenade at his unit as he tried to "establish authority," according to local reports.
The blast reportedly occurred at a military facility in Belgorod region's Korochansky district on January 14.

Belgorod is located near the Ukrainian border and houses several Russian military bases and training grounds.

According to Baza, a Russian Telegram channel that regularly posts information about security issues within the country, the explosion occurred at a cultural center re-purposed to house mobilized troops.

Russian emergency services told the state-run news agency Interfax that the sergeant accidentally detonated a hand grenade which caused ammunition to blow up and started a fire.

Baza said the man who caused the blast "picked up an RGD-5 grenade in order to establish authority over his troops."

"After the explosion, which took place in a cultural center housing mobilized soldiers, ammunition detonated and a fire erupted over an area of 450 square meters. It took firefighters about four hours to extinguish it." Baza reported.

Newsweek has been unable to independently verify the report, and has reached out to Russia's foreign ministry for comment.

Source: https://www.newsweek.com/commander-belgorod-ammunition-explosion-russia-1774066

title: People paddling around in a restricted Manatee Sanctuary
description:
This is an "all day every day" occurrence in Tampa Bay in the winter. Kayakers and motor boats going into the Manatee Sanctuary. 
Some people just feel entitled, others don't care because they don't understand. Since they don't understand why they aren't allowed, they do it anyway, instead of educating themselves about why it's wrong. 
There's a lot of reasons we have Manatee sanctuaries and laws to protect Manatees. Aside from the common knowledge that Manatees and boats are a bad mix, here's a few other reasons why it's wrong to disturb manatees, especially Manatees in a sanctuary.... 
Although Manatees are curious and friendly with people, they prefer to initiate the encounter and don't always feel like being social or being disturbed, just like people. When you paddle right up to Manatees, your presence often causes them to leave the area. And although this may not seem like a big deal, when human activity/pressure causes manatees to leave their hangout spots in the winter, such as warm water springs, they can die from cold stress. During other times of year, human activity or pressure can cause them to leave the safety of canals or just a patch of water off to the side of a busy waterway, and it often sends them out into boat traffic to find another spot. 

All of the pics and videos I post are taken by me. For more OC (original content) nature vids check out my gallery at https://imgur.com/user/SeeThroughCanoe/posts
